    {
      "id": "4b807c918a1de4a6af270b9eaeffd6a5198645f8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-23 15:18:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(9 inline comments)\n\nSome major problems with this patch:\n- it checks for the DESTROY_PENDING flag on the object, but never sets this flag anywhere\n- too many retries\n- why is there IO happening on the object when it is being destroyed?  The destroy should only be sent after all clients have closed the file and it is unlinked on the MDS. When the destroy is handled on the OST it should also cause all of the extent locks to be cancelled with a special flag in the callback to force clients to discard their data. This ensures there are not continuous writes happening on a destroyed object.  Please verify if this is actually working correctly.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5ca875a15c40a903cb9d95caa221c62599ffe252",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 144,
        "name": "Hongchao Zhang",
        "email": "hongchao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "Hongchao.zhang"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 04:07:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (7 inline comments)\n\nthe main problem to fix is the race between the object destory sent by MDT and the writing from Clients.\nafter the client deleted the file, there are still write requests pending to send to OST for the client\ndoesn't know whether the inode of the file is really deleted by MDT(there could be other links to the inode).\n\nthis problem is highlighted by the run_dd.sh test, which run \"dd\" in a loop.\n\nnormally, this issue could not be so distinct.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "fa34be9d1c7bc081485b88cba1b66680497106aa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 11:10:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\ncan you describe exactly the case? like Andreas said this should not happen to regular cached IO (covered with LDLM locks).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
